''See also: [[Acrobat]]''
==English==
===Etymology===
Fr. ''acrobate'', from [[Ancient Greek]] '''[[ακροβάτης]]''' (''akrobates'') "walking on tiptoe, climbing aloft", from '''[[ακροβατέω]]''' (''akrobateo'') "to walk on tiptoe", from '''[[άκρον]]''' (''akron'') "highest or farthest point, mountain top, peak" + '''[[βατής]]''' (''bates'') "one that treads or covers", an inflection of '''[[βαίνω]]''' (''baino'') "to walk, to step".

===Pronunciation===
IPA: [[WEAE]] /ˈæk.ɹo.bæt/

===Noun===
'''acrobat'''
#An [[athlete]] who performs acts requiring [[skill]], [[agility]] and [[coordination]].

====Translations====
*Finnish: [[akrobaatti]]
*Greek: [[ακροβάτης]] (''akrovates'') {{m}}

